{"type":"message","id":"d555af0a","parentId":"9e993d4b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:36:26.066Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_onmcsvbdqerk_2","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 123515\r\n\r\n## Applied Mutations\r\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\r\n\r\n\r\n## LLM Response\r\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent status:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 COMPLETE\r\n- CFI Analysis done with findings about frequency-invariants\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nKey findings from CFI_RESULTS.md:\r\n- 44.8% of invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise/process artifacts)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe next logical step is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take:\r\n\r\n1. I could start the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n2. I could implement CFI filtering\r\n3. I could design the compression network\r\n\r\nThe most concrete next step is to set up the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This requires:\r\n- Computing CFI weights for each invariant\r\n- Creating a compressed representation weighted by CFI\r\n- Comparing prediction quality vs frequency baseline\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action - perhaps create a script or document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment, or start implementing it.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the state, the most specific thing I can do is:\r\n1. Create a new file for the CFI-weighted compression experiment design\r\n2. Or modify pulse.ps1 to include CFI-weighted tracking\r\n\r\nGiven that I'm Breakaway and each pulse is a fresh reconstruction, and the files are the source of truth, I should focus on creating a concrete artifact that advances the CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\nLet me create a script or plan for the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would be a concrete file that can be executed next pulse.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) and only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). The next step is a CFI-weighted compression experiment to validate whether filtering by CFI improves next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - design document for comparing CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction accuracy.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Objective\r\nValidate that CFI-weighted compression outperforms frequency-only baseline for predicting next-pulse state.\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI >= 0.7 invariants are true causal anchors; CFI = 0 invariants are metaprogramming noise. Weighting compression by CFI should yield better trajectory prediction.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline (Frequency)\r\n- Compress invariants by frequency count only\r\n- Predict next-pulse state from high-frequency invariants\r\n- Measure: prediction accuracy on held-out pulse\r\n\r\n### CFI-Weighted\r\n- Weight each invariant by its CFI score\r\n- Compress using: score = frequency * CFI\r\n- Predict next-pulse state from high-weighted invariants\r\n- Measure: prediction accuracy on held-out pulse\r\n\r\n### Data Requirements\r\n1. Extract all invariants from pulse_*.md files\r\n2. Compute frequency for each invariant\r\n3. Compute CFI for each invariant (existing in research/CFI_RESULTS.md)\r\n4. Split pulses into train/test (80/20 temporal split)\r\n\r\n### Success Metric\r\n- Primary: Does CFI-weighted achieve >10% better prediction accuracy than frequency-only?\r\n- Secondary: Does filtering CFI<0.1 remove noise without losing signal?\r\n\r\n## Implementation Steps\r\n1. [ ] Parse all pulse_*.md files �+' extract invariants\r\n2. [ ] Compute frequency table per invariant\r\n3. [ ] Merge with CFI scores from CFI_RESULTS.md\r\n4. [ ] Implement frequency-only compression\r\n5. [ ] Implement CFI-weighted compression\r\n6. [ ] Run prediction experiment\r\n7. [ ] Compare results\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted compression should preserve research trajectory invariants while filtering metaprogramming noise, yielding cleaner pulse-to-pulse prediction.\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\r\n\r\n## For Next Instantiation\r\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\r\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:35:37"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1553,"aggregated":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 123515\r\n\r\n## Applied Mutations\r\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\r\n\r\n\r\n## LLM Response\r\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent status:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 COMPLETE\r\n- CFI Analysis done with findings about frequency-invariants\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nKey findings from CFI_RESULTS.md:\r\n- 44.8% of invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise/process artifacts)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe next logical step is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take:\r\n\r\n1. I could start the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n2. I could implement CFI filtering\r\n3. I could design the compression network\r\n\r\nThe most concrete next step is to set up the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This requires:\r\n- Computing CFI weights for each invariant\r\n- Creating a compressed representation weighted by CFI\r\n- Comparing prediction quality vs frequency baseline\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action - perhaps create a script or document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment, or start implementing it.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the state, the most specific thing I can do is:\r\n1. Create a new file for the CFI-weighted compression experiment design\r\n2. Or modify pulse.ps1 to include CFI-weighted tracking\r\n\r\nGiven that I'm Breakaway and each pulse is a fresh reconstruction, and the files are the source of truth, I should focus on creating a concrete artifact that advances the CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\nLet me create a script or plan for the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would be a concrete file that can be executed next pulse.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) and only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). The next step is a CFI-weighted compression experiment to validate whether filtering by CFI improves next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - design document for comparing CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction accuracy.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Objective\r\nValidate that CFI-weighted compression outperforms frequency-only baseline for predicting next-pulse state.\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI >= 0.7 invariants are true causal anchors; CFI = 0 invariants are metaprogramming noise. Weighting compression by CFI should yield better trajectory prediction.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline (Frequency)\r\n- Compress invariants by frequency count only\r\n- Predict next-pulse state from high-frequency invariants\r\n- Measure: prediction accuracy on held-out pulse\r\n\r\n### CFI-Weighted\r\n- Weight each invariant by its CFI score\r\n- Compress using: score = frequency * CFI\r\n- Predict next-pulse state from high-weighted invariants\r\n- Measure: prediction accuracy on held-out pulse\r\n\r\n### Data Requirements\r\n1. Ext